\par\plain {Madeleine\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s boots clicked softly on the stone path as she crossed the campus grounds, the foggy air curling around her like ghostly ribbons. Her scarf was pulled tight around her neck, and she buttoned her coat all the way up, her gloved hands tucked into her sleeves to fend off the creeping cold.}
\par\plain {The lamplight from the faculty buildings spilled in golden puddles onto the walkway, but the rest of Edenfield was dim and quiet\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 students tucked away in their dorms or libraries, the hum of campus life reduced to stillness.}
\par\plain {She reached the bus stop at the edge of the quad, where the wrought-iron sign swayed slightly in the breeze. The enchanted schedule flickered faintly, glowing with runes that shifted to show }{\f0\fs24\i1 Aetherell Reach \endash  6 min.}
\par\plain {With a quiet sigh, Madeleine sat down on the bench, the cold seeping through the wooden slats. She leaned back and let her head tilt toward the sky, watching her breath fog in the moonlight. }
\par\plain {Her gaze drifted out across the empty road, unfocused.}
\par\plain {But her thoughts didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t stay still for long. They circled back\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 inevitably\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 to her conversation with Walther.}
\par\plain {He\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d acted strangely. Not }{\f0\fs24\i1 obviously}{ so, but off. She\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d known him since the start of term, shared a lab bench with him more days than not. He was reliable. Reserved. Never the type to get worked up about\u8230\'85 }{\f0\fs24\i1 anything}{, let alone one of her messy drawings.}
\par\plain {He had never shown the slightest interest in her sketches before. Never once asked her where she got her ideas, let alone stared at one like he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d seen a ghost.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\i1 Why today?}
\par\plain {Then it hit her. }{\f0\fs24\i1 Of course.}{ Walther had mentioned in passing\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 once, maybe twice\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 that he was studying the anatomy and vascular structures of South Alamirian Tigers. That was probably why the drawing caught his eye. That had to be it.}
\par\plain {Still, something didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t sit right.}
\par\plain {She sat up straighter, her fingers curling against her knees. }{\f0\fs24\i1 Wait.}
\par\plain {Walther volunteered at the Sanctuary. But unlike her\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 who cleaned enclosures, administered salves, handled creature check-ups\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Walther never worked in the physical sections. He was never on feeding duty, never in the recovery stables, never doing the dirty work. His role was\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 research. Always research.}
\par\plain {He studied the creatures. Dissected their physiology through observation and notes. He didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t }{\f0\fs24\i1 care}{ for them. He }{\f0\fs24\i1 studied}{ them.}
\par\plain {And there was more. He volunteered with Edenfield\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s Food Shelter Society. Madeleine remembered him saying that once, off-handedly, like it didn\u8217\'92t matter. They helped the city\u8217\'92s unhoused population. They delivered food, yes\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but also went into places people didn\u8217\'92t like to talk about. Old tunnels, abandoned corners of the city. The underbelly.}
\par\plain {Two things clicked. Then three. Then four.}
\par\plain {Madeleine\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s breath caught in her throat.}
\par\plain {Research\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 deep anatomical knowledge\u8230\'85 access to vulnerable populations\u8230\'85 a strange, cold fascination with a creature that shouldn\u8217\'92t exist\u8230\'85}
\par\plain {Her hand flew to her satchel, as if instinctively checking her sketches were still there.}
\par\plain {Her face slowly paled, lips parting slightly as a horrible thought took shape. Not fully formed\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but enough to cast a shadow over everything she\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d been trying to ignore.}
\par\plain {Could it be?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\i1 No. No, that\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s insane\u8230\'85}{ she told herself. But her gut didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t agree. Her heart was thudding now, dull and fast beneath her scarf. The pieces didn\u8217\'92t fit perfectly\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but they sat too close not to touch.}
\par\plain {The wind picked up again, rustling the trees behind the shelter.}
\par\plain {Madeleine stared ahead, her eyes wide, her breath held.}
\par\plain {The bus rolled up in the distance. But she no longer felt the comfort of home awaiting her. Only a hollow, rising dread.}
